This paper deals with the problem of efficiently solving partially observable Markov decision processes (POMDPs) using approximation methods. This is a problem that is relevant to several subfields of computer science, including artificial intelligence (cs.AI), machine learning (cs.LG), robotics (cs.RO), control systems (cs.SY), and data structures and algorithms (cs.DS). Given that the paper focuses on both theoretical analysis and experimental evaluation of approximation methods, it is likely to be of interest to researchers in these subfields.
